Project: Wrangle and Analyze Data¶

This Udacity project aims to practice a typical data wrangling process. This includes gathering data from a variety of sources, such as CSV-files, TSV-files and an API: The Twitter-API. Then its cleanly- and tidiness will be assessed in order to correct quality issues, converting the data to a tidy dataset. This happens according to the rules of tidiness https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/tidyr/vignettes/tidy-data.html. Once quality and tidiness is assured, the sources will be combined to one or more master datasets before finally analyzing and visualizing it.

Note: Assessing and wrangling the entirety of the dataset would require more time than provided by Udacity. They, therefore, required to find at least eight quality and two tidiness issues to be assessed and cleaned. Keep in mind, there may be more issues still present.

tweets_json_lake = []
In [ ]:
# Measuring elapsed time for retrieving information from the Twitter API.
start_time_twitter_api = time.time()

# Iterating through all tweet ids to retrieve the entire post as an object.
for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
    # Using the try-and-except method to handle non-existing tweet_ids: Cases where no information can be obtained.   
    try:
        # Using the get_status function of tweepy to retrieve the post, including the retweeted and favorite counts.
        tweet_status = api.get_status(tweet_id, wait_on_rate_limit=True, wait_on_rate_limit_notify=True)
        # Appending the tweet (as a json-object to the list of tweets)
        tweets_json_lake.append(tweet_status._json)
        # Empyting variable for the next iteration
        tweet_status = ""
        #print(str(tweet_id)) #Can be used to monitor
    except:
        print("Retrieving information of tweet ID " + str(tweet_id) + " failed.")
In [ ]:
# Creating or opening the file tweets_json.text in write mode, to put the list of tweets into.
with open ('input_raw_data/tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    json.dump(tweets_json_lake, outfile)
    
print("Tweet information stored to file.")
#Stop timing
end_time_twitter_api = time.time()
print("Elapsed time for retrieving tweet information: " + str(end_time_twitter_api - start_time_twitter_api) + "seconds.")

Please note: The last five cells were executed only once, in order to retrieve the information from the Twitter API. Once the information was retrieved I did not run those cells anymore, hence the missing output. This due to the fact that running the concern tweet ids throught the API takes 20-30 minutes each time.

# It may occur, that when the python notebook ran twice or more times, without first deleting the tweet_json.txt file,
# that duplicates will be created as the API calls are simply appended to the file. 
# The easiest way is to deduplicate the data frame before continuing the analysis.

# It may also occur, that the python notebook ran at different days, meanwhile the performance of a tweet
# has increased (i.e. has higher retweet or favorite count). Hence, the row as a whole would not be a duplicate anymore. 
# Checking if there are any duplicate tweet_ids are existent.

print("Duplicates before cleaning: "+ str(sum(df_tweet_performance.tweet_id.duplicated())))

The observations and issues to this dataset as listed below. This serves as a summary.

General Observations¶

The following points cannot be categorized as issues. These point are of a general nature and need to be adressed and handled prior to the analysis. The handling is described in the section "General Preparations" in the "Cleaning Data" section.

  1. According to the instructions tweets beyond August 1st, 2017 shall not be included in the analysis as no prediction of the breed (by image) is available for that period. The concerning post data shall be deleted from the twitter_archive dataset.
  2. Missing values in columns in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id. Since these values are optional values they can be ignored. Furthermore, both columns have the same amount of values. This implies consistency, as the columns relate to each other.
  3. Missing values in columns retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp. Since these values are optional values they can be ignored. Furthermore, both columns have the same amount of values. This implies consistency, as the columns relate to each other.
  4. According to the instructions retweets and replies will not be part of the analysis. Rows with values can be dropped. Then the empty columns can be dropped as well.
  5. The fact that rating numerators are (mostly) greater than the denominators does not need to be cleaned according to the project's instructions. This is seen as part of the unique rating system of WeRateDogs.

Quality Issues¶

  1. Missing values in column expanded_urls. Every post should be related to a rated dog picture (there should be a value for every post id/row). The image is the essential basis for the analysis. Rows with empty values shall be deleted.
  2. Everypost should be related to rated dog picture (there should be a value for every post id/row). A deep dive into this column reveals the following shortcomings: multiple entries, whereas, only one value per row and column is favorable. By sampling visually it appears that the multiples are often just duplicate values within one cell. The redundant information shall be extracted.
  3. Duplicate expanded_urls present: most duplicated image URLs are present in rows with retweets. For the purpose of analysis, rows with retweets will not be part of it and can, therefore, be deleted. However, I discovered at least one real duplicate. Hence deleted rows with duplicate expanded_urls is necessary.
  4. The columns rating_numerator and rating_denominator have partly rare and illogical values. Analysis revealed these outlying values can be explained as typos, incorrect extraction from the post and exaggeration. Leaving them be would make any analysis invalid. When considering values higher than 20 and lower than 1 as illogical, only very few rows are affected (26 and 23), they shall be deleted. Deeper inspection and correcting them would consume too much time.
  5. The rating numerator and denominator represent a single variable stored in different columns. They should therefore be divided and stored into a new single column.
  6. Column source: There are no values implying any of these tweets have been posted by an Android app/device. At first glance, this appears to be odd. Given the fact that all tweets could have been posted by just a few people mostly using Apple devices, this shall not be of further interest. The column can, therefore, be dropped. Sidenote: in terms of quality the column contains irrelevant information "https://.....". The essential part is stored in the hyperlink text itself and could be extracted from the rest if needed.

Tidiness Issues¶

    Optional, in case analysis would be extended to replies and retweets:
  1. The column set of "in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id" and "retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp" form different sets of observational units are can therefore be separated from the rest of the data by storing each set into a new table. The column tweet_id can be used as a 1 to 1 or identifier.

    2. Optional if analysis would need to cover the special classifications "doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo"
  2. The columns doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo are untidy as the values are stored in column names. These can be combined to one column stating the "special classification". For the purpose of this analysis, these columns shall be dropped.

Note to the reviewer: I left it integer because this type consumes less storage capacity and this there faster in handling.

Quality Issues¶

  1. Duplicated image URLs: assessment revealed there are 66 duplicates entries present, however, each pair has a different tweet id. Further assessment showed the same amounts of duplicates among all image prediction value columns, implying that a pair of duplicates is predicated equally. Therefore these duplicates will not be removed. That way, chances are higher that an image prediction is available for each tweet id from the twitter archive dataset.
  2. The false values of the columns p1 to p4_dog imply not all images are showing dogs. Manual sampling revealed chances are high the image contains a dog when at least one of the values per is row is true. All other rows shall be deleted.
  3. The columns p1, p2, p3 have mixed capitalization. Each first letter of a word will be capitalized. That may also reduce different writings of dog breeds, if existent. This might make the analysis more valid.
  4. In the columns p1, p2, p3 single words are separated by an underscore. Underscores will be replaced by spaces.
  5. The column img_num will be dropped. The reason, why this is an issue of quality: the values in this column do not explain themselves. They therefore might be misinterpreted and should be excluded as a precaution.

Tidiness Issues¶

  1. The columns "p1, p1_conf, p1_dog, etc." have parts of their values in the column titles. The order of the predictions, which is actually a value and cannot be part of the title. To make this tidy, the layout would need to be changed to: "p, p_conf, p_dog" + an additional column "p_order" to state the order of the prediction 1 for the first try, 2 for the second and 3 for the third.
  2. The fact that the data of the same observational unit (i.e. the Tweet iself) is stored is present across three separate tables is a tidiness issue. Merging them to one single table is the fix. It also makes analysis easier.

# separate sources (joined).
df_twitter_combined.to_sql('df_twitter_combined_master', engine, index=False)
